  "prompt": "Why is sodium hydrogen carbonate soluble in water?",
  "response": "Sodium hydrogen carbonate (NaHCO\u2083), also known as sodium bicarbonate or baking soda, is soluble in water due to its ionic nature and the interactions it has with water molecules.\n\nHere are a few reasons that explain its solubility:\n\n1. **Ionic Compound**: Sodium hydrogen carbonate is composed of sodium ions (Na\u207a) and bicarbonate ions (HCO\u2083\u207b). As an ionic compound, it can dissociate into these ions when added to water.\n\n2. **Hydration Shells**: Water is a polar solvent, meaning it has a partial positive charge on one side (due to the hydrogen atoms) and a partial negative charge on the other side (due to the oxygen atom). When NaHCO\u2083 is added to water, the positive sodium ions are attracted to the negative oxygen ends of water molecules, while the negative bicarbonate ions are attracted to the positive hydrogen ends. This interaction allows the ions to become surrounded by water molecules, forming hydration shells that help to keep the ions in solution.\n\n3. **Energy Considerations**: The energy released when the water molecules surround and stabilize the dissociated ions is greater than the energy required to break the ionic bonds in sodium hydrogen carbonate. This favorable energy balance contributes to its solubility.\n\n4. **Equilibrium**: When added to water, sodium hydrogen carbonate will dissociate, and this process reaches an equilibrium where some ions remain associated, while many ions remain free in solution. \n\nOverall, the combination of its ionic character and the stabilizing effect of water molecules leads to the solubility of sodium hydrogen carbonate in water.",
